The '''Carabobo-1 oil field''' is an [[oil field]] located in the [[Orinoco Belt]]. It was discovered in 2010 and developed by [[PDVSA]]. The oil field is operated and owned by [[PDVSA]]. The total [[proven reserves]] of the Carabobo-1 oil field are around {{convert|50|e9oilbbl}}, and production is centered on {{convert|400000|oilbbl/d|m3/d}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cerebralbusiness.com/KnowledgeBase/News/Reliance-eyes-Venezuela-block-203504.htm |title=Reliance eyes Venezuela block |year=2014 |publisher=cerebralbusiness.com |accessdate=2014-04-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430042942/http://www.cerebralbusiness.com/KnowledgeBase/News/Reliance-eyes-Venezuela-block-203504.htm |archivedate=2014-04-30 |df= }}</ref>

Indian state-owned company [[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation|ONGC Videsh Ltd.]] (OVL) helped certify heavy oil reserves in the Orinoco river belt in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theworldreporter.com/2013/03/hugo-chavez-foreign-relations-and-policies.html|title=Hugo Chavez's Foreign Policies and International Relations|publisher=The World Reporter|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sreeharsha|first1=Vinod|title=India and Venezuela: a success story|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-opinion/india-and-venezuela-a-success-story/article3052450.ece|website=The Hindu|accessdate=8 January 2017|date=25 November 2006}}</ref> In February 2010, an international consortium comprising OVL, [[Indian Oil Corporation]] (IOC), [[Oil India]], [[Repsol]] of Spain and [[Petronas]] of Malaysia won a global bid to claim a 40% stake worth $1.05 billion in the Carabobo-1 oil field.<ref>{{cite web|title=OVL team bags 40% in Venezuela oil block|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-02-12/news/27579178_1_oil-block-carabobo-1-junin/2|website=The Economic Times|date=12 February 2010|accessdate=8 January 2017|page=2}}</ref>

